# Zod — TypeScript-First Schema Validation

Zod lets you define a schema, validate data against it at runtime, and infer the TypeScript type — all from a single source of truth.

## Installation

```bash
npm install zod
# or
pnpm add zod
# or
yarn add zod
# or
bun add zod
```

Requires TypeScript >=5.5 with `"strict": true` in tsconfig.json.

## Quick Start

```typescript
import { z } from "zod";

// Define a schema
const UserSchema = z.object({
  name: z.string().min(1),
  email: z.string().email(),
  age: z.number().int().positive(),
  role: z.enum(["admin", "user", "guest"]),
});

// Infer the TypeScript type
type User = z.infer<typeof UserSchema>;
// { name: string; email: string; age: number; role: "admin" | "user" | "guest" }

// Parse unknown data — throws ZodError on failure
const user = UserSchema.parse(unknownInput);

// Safe parse — returns { success, data } or { success, error }
const result = UserSchema.safeParse(unknownInput);
if (result.success) {
  console.log(result.data); // fully typed User
} else {
  console.log(result.error.flatten()); // structured error object
}
```

## Child Nodes

- **[[zod/schemas]]** — Define schemas for every data shape: primitives, objects, arrays, enums, unions, tuples, records
- **[[zod/validation]]** — Validate, refine, and constrain data with built-in validators and custom refinements
- **[[zod/transform]]** — Transform, coerce, preprocess, and pipe data through schema chains
- **[[zod/inference]]** — Extract TypeScript types from schemas with z.infer, z.input, z.output
- **[[zod/patterns]]** — Common Zod patterns: API validation, form schemas, env parsing, discriminated unions, recursive types

## Why Zod

| Feature | Zod | io-ts | yup | joi |
|---------|-----|-------|-----|-----|
| TypeScript-first | Yes | Yes | Partial | No |
| Zero deps | Yes | fp-ts | Yes | No |
| Type inference | Yes | Yes | Partial | No |
| Transforms | Yes | Yes | Yes | Yes |
| Async validation | Yes | Yes | Yes | Yes |
| Bundle size | 2kb | 5kb | 12kb | 30kb |

## Environment Variables

Zod itself requires no environment variables. It is a pure library.

| Variable | Purpose |
|----------|----------|
| `NODE_ENV` | When set to `production`, some frameworks strip Zod error messages for smaller bundles |
